"A maze is a grid where some cells are walls and some cells are open.
A path is a sequence of open cells from start to goal, each cell
adjacent to the previous. A pathfinder is a program that finds a
path given the maze, the start, and the goal. This chapter builds
one, uses it to steer agents, and then makes the maze move under the
agents so they have to re-plan.

Pathfinding is not magic. It is search over a graph. The graph is
'open cells linked to their open neighbors,' and the algorithm is
called A-star (spelled A*). A* keeps a frontier of cells it hasn't
examined yet, ordered by a smart guess of how close each is to the
goal, and expands the best-looking cell first. When it reaches the
goal, it reconstructs the path by walking back through remembered
parents. That is the whole algorithm.

Motoi Scheme's `ai/path` wraps A* so you don't write it yourself, but
we'll build a tiny version by hand so you can see the shape.

---

## 6.1 A maze

```scheme
(define (make-maze cols rows)
  (let ((g (ai/grid cols rows)))
    ;; Walls around the edge.
    (let loop-x ((c 0))
      (when (< c cols)
        (ai/wall! g c 0)
        (ai/wall! g c (- rows 1))
        (loop-x (+ c 1))))
    (let loop-y ((r 0))
      (when (< r rows)
        (ai/wall! g 0 r)
        (ai/wall! g (- cols 1) r)
        (loop-y (+ r 1))))
    ;; A few internal walls to make it interesting.
    (for-each
      (lambda (rc)
        (ai/wall! g (car rc) (cdr rc)))
      '((5 . 4) (5 . 5) (5 . 6) (5 . 7)
        (10 . 8) (10 . 9) (10 . 10) (10 . 11)
        (15 . 3) (15 . 4) (15 . 5) (15 . 6)
        (15 . 7) (15 . 8)))
    g))

(define maze (make-maze 24 16))
```

`ai/grid` creates the pathfinding grid; `ai/wall!` marks a cell as
non-traversable. Now we have a grid with obstacles.

## 6.2 Find a path

```scheme
(define path (ai/path maze '(2 . 2) '(21 . 13)))
;; => ((2 . 2) (3 . 2) (4 . 2) ... (21 . 13))
```

`ai/path` returns a list of cell coordinates from start to goal, or
`#f` if no path exists. Under the hood, A* has:

- Kept a priority queue of cells to examine, ordered by `g + h`,
  where `g` is the cost to reach the cell from the start and `h` is
  a HEURISTIC — a fast, admissible guess at cost from the cell to
  the goal. On a grid, `h` is usually Manhattan distance.
- Popped the cheapest cell, marked it examined, and expanded its
  passable neighbors, updating their `g` and remembering their
  parent.
- Stopped when it popped the goal, at which point it walked parents
  back to reconstruct the path.

That is A*. Every game AI you've ever seen doing pathfinding uses
some form of it.

## 6.3 Walk the path

```scheme
(define (spawn-agent x y)
  (let ((a (world/spawn 'runner x y)))
    (entity/mass!      a 1.0)
    (entity/max-speed! a 1.5)
    (ai/max-force!     a 0.10)
    a))

(define runner (spawn-agent 32 32))

(ai/follow-path runner path)
```

`ai/follow-path` installs a steering behavior on the agent. Each
frame the agent computes 'which waypoint am I heading for now?' and
steers toward it. When it reaches a waypoint, it advances to the
next. When it reaches the last waypoint, it stops.

The waypoint spacing matters. If waypoints are too dense, the agent
zigzags between them; if too sparse, it takes shortcuts and clips
through corners. `ai/waypoints` can down-sample a path by removing
collinear points, which usually gives better-looking motion.

```scheme
(define smoothed (ai/waypoints path))
(ai/follow-path runner smoothed)
```

## 6.4 Visualize the search

Watching A* explore is one of the delightful things about it.
`ai/path-debug` returns the search-order too, so you can paint each
explored cell in fading color.

```scheme
(let ((debug (ai/path-debug maze '(2 . 2) '(21 . 13))))
  (let ((order (assoc 'explored debug))
        (path  (assoc 'path     debug)))
    (on-frame
      (lambda (t)
        ;; Paint each explored cell, colored by order.
        (for-each
          (lambda (cell-and-time)
            (let ((c    (car  cell-and-time))
                  (when (cadr cell-and-time)))
              (paint-cell (car c) (cdr c) (color-fade when))))
          (cdr order))
        ;; Overlay the path in bright.
        (for-each
          (lambda (c) (paint-cell (car c) (cdr c) yellow))
          (cdr path))))))
```

You see A* radiating out from the start, biased toward the goal (that
is the heuristic doing its work), then a bright path drawn on top when
it reaches. Kids love this. It demystifies AI.

## 6.5 Dynamic maze — re-plan under change

Drop a wall in front of the agent mid-run. The agent has to notice
and re-plan.

```scheme
(define (drop-wall-and-replan)
  (ai/wall! maze 15 12)                 ;; block a cell on the path
  (let* ((from (entity/cell runner))
         (new  (ai/path maze from '(21 . 13))))
    (if new
        (ai/follow-path runner (ai/waypoints new))
        (display \"stuck\"))))
```

You could do this on every keypress, or on every wall-drop, or
continuously (re-plan every N frames). Continuous replanning is what
real games do for enemies chasing a player who moves. It's cheap
enough on small grids to run every frame.

## 6.6 Guards on patrol — a stealth mini-sim

Give some guards a fixed patrol path (a loop). Give the player a
different goal. Ask: is there a path the player can take that never
puts them in a guard's sight for the next 30 frames?

```scheme
(define guard-1 (spawn-agent 96 96))
(define guard-1-path (ai/waypoints
  (ai/path maze '(3 . 3) '(3 . 12))))
(ai/follow-path-loop guard-1 guard-1-path)

;; Predict where each guard will be in the next 30 frames.
(define (guard-forecast guard n)
  (let loop ((i 0) (positions '()))
    (if (>= i n)
        (reverse positions)
        (loop (+ i 1)
              (cons (ai/predict-position guard i)
                    positions)))))

;; A cell is 'unsafe' if any guard sees it within the next 30 frames.
(define (unsafe? cell)
  (let ((forecasts
          (map (lambda (g) (guard-forecast g 30))
               (world/find-all 'runner))))
    (any (lambda (fs)
           (any (lambda (p) (< (geom/distance cell p) 3)) fs))
         forecasts)))

;; A pathfind that treats unsafe cells as walls.
(define (safe-path from to)
  (let ((snapshot (ai/grid-copy maze)))
    (for-each
      (lambda (cell) (ai/wall! snapshot (car cell) (cdr cell)))
      (unsafe-cells snapshot 30))
    (ai/path snapshot from to)))
```

This is game design as pathfinding-plus-prediction. Each guard's
future path is a spacetime tube; the player's plan avoids the tubes.

---

## 6.7 The four routing patterns in pathfinding

**Composition.** The pathfinder is composed: heuristic function +
priority queue + explored set + parent map. `ai/path` is a
composition of those pieces. In-house you'd swap the heuristic to
Chebyshev or Euclidean or a domain-specific one.

**Orchestration.** A guard's life cycle is orchestrated: pick a patrol
target → path to it → follow the path → pick the next target → repeat.
The stealth game's player-plan is orchestrated across time: forecast
guards → wall-off unsafe cells → replan → move for K frames → forecast
again.

**In-routing.** When the agent reaches a waypoint, the follow-path
routine advances to the next. This is a mini in-router — the event
'reached waypoint N' dispatches to 'set current target to waypoint N+1'
or 'stop.' When a wall drops, an event like `world/on-grid-change`
routes to a re-planner.

**Routing.** The path itself is a route in the physical sense (the
agent's route through the maze). The exploration visualization routes
each explored cell to the framebuffer. The 'no path exists' outcome
routes to the game's failure handler ('the level is unsolvable, tell
the operator'). The runtime can persist to Cortex: 'from the shop's stock
room, average path length to the checkout with this shelf
arrangement is 14 cells.'

---

## 6.8 Common desktop tasks

An operator asked: 'if we rearrange the shop, will customers still be
able to reach every product?' Model the shop as a grid, model the
shelves as walls, run `ai/path` from the entrance to each product's
cell. If any product returns no path, you've boxed it in. Also useful:
compute the average path length from entrance to each shelf as a
'reachability score.'

## 6.9 Try this

1. Add DIAGONAL neighbors (`ai/grid-8-connected`). Do paths get
   shorter? Do they look more natural?
2. Turn some walls into 'expensive' cells (`ai/cost-set! g x y 5`).
   Does A* route around them?
3. Two agents, both pathfinding to the same goal. Do they collide?
   Fix it: teach the pathfinder that another agent's next 5 cells
   are temporarily walls.
4. Fog of war: `ai/path` on a partial map (only cells the agent has
   visited). Does the agent explore intelligently?
5. Compare A* to breadth-first search (`ai/path :heuristic 'zero`)
   on a big open grid. Which explores fewer cells?

## 6.10 Pitfalls

**Unreachable goal.** `ai/path` returns `#f`. Always handle this in
your caller.

**Bad heuristic.** If the heuristic overestimates distance to goal,
A* is no longer optimal — it may return a suboptimal path. Manhattan
is safe on 4-connected grids; Chebyshev is safe on 8-connected.

**Grid resolution.** Too fine, and paths are jaggy AND expensive to
compute. Too coarse, and paths miss the natural shape of your world.
The right resolution matches the agent's collision size.

---

Next: the brachistochrone. What curve gets a ball from A to B
fastest? Not the straight line, not the quarter circle. Something
older and stranger.")
